<HEADLINE>
<P>
CUBA CUTTING OFF NICARAGUA AID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MEXICO CITY 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cuban President Fidel Castro said Wednesday that he is cutting off all military 
aid to Nicaragua before the new government takes office next month, Cuba's 
official news agency Prensa Latina reported. 
</P>
<P>
Castro said Cuban assistance in housing construction and health care could 
continue if Nicaragua's new government desires, but Cuba would no longer supply 
Nicaragua with petroleum and food. 
</P>
<P>
Castro has close ties with Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government, which was 
upset in the Feb. 25 election. President-elect Violeta Barrios de Chamorro was 
strongly supported by Castro's archenemy, the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
