<HEADLINE>
<P>
PHOENIX GROUP, DCM TENTATIVELY AGREE TO LICENSING, MARKETING PLAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By from Staff Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
IRVINE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Phoenix Group International Inc. said Wednesday that it has reached a tentative 
technology licensing and marketing agreement with DCM Data Products of India. 
</P>
<P>
Phoenix Group Chairman Charles W. Missler said the preliminary agreement calls 
for DCM to manufacture terminals and local area network products developed by 
Phoenix's fledgling Netcom Research. 
</P>
<P>
Phoenix will market DCM's IBM compatible personal computers and a new 
minicomputer based on the Intel 486 processor. 
</P>
<P>
Missler said DCM was a leading company in India with revenues of about $50 
million. 
</P>
<P>
Phoenix Group, a collection of small technology companies based in Irvine, last 
year announced a contract to sell 6 million personal computers to the Soviet 
Union for use in its schools. But only 770 computers have been shipped so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
