<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
PEUGEOT TIES WITH FIAT URGED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PARIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The French government suggested today that Peugeot, the nation's largest 
private industrial company, link up with Fiat of Italy to form an auto group 
big enough to withstand growing Japanese competition in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
The comment from a highly placed French official was made days after 
Daimler-Benz AG of West Germany and Mitsubishi Corp. of Japan announced a 
wide-ranging cooperation agreement involving cars and other industrial sectors. 
In addition, Volvo and Renault have entered a similar agreement. 
</P>
<P>
The official, briefing journalists on condition he not be identified, said the 
government expects one or two of the six major European car manufacturers to 
disappear within the next 10 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
