<HEADLINE>
<P>
FCC MAY GIVE AT&amp;T MORE FREEDOM TO VIE WITH ITS RIVALS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Federal Communications Commission today proposed to loosen its regulation 
of AT&amp;T, saying the one-time phone monopoly now faces "significant 
competition" in the interstate long-distance marketplace. 
</P>
<P>
The commission, in a 4-0 vote, adopted a staff proposal that, if finally 
approved, would give the American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. some of the 
freedom it says it needs to maneuver against competitors such as MCI 
Communications Corp. and US Sprint. 
</P>
<P>
The FCC last year gave AT&amp;T a major deregulatory victory when it dumped its 
20-year rate-of-return regulation of AT&amp;T's profits in exchange for a 
system that controls AT&amp;T's prices within certain limits tied to the rate 
of inflation. 
</P>
<P>
The commission proposed phased-in changes in certain business services, 
extending later to 800 services, international messaging and operator services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
