<HEADLINE>
<P>
COURT PLACES NETS' SHACKLEFORD INTO PRE-TRIAL PROGRAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ORANGE, N.J. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New Jersey Nets forward Charles Shackleford was placed in a pre-trial 
intervention program today at a court hearing into marijuana possession charges 
against him. 
</P>
<P>
Shackleford's attorney, Matthew Boylan, acknowledged that his client was 
carrying marijuana when he was arrested March 1, but Shackleford did not enter 
a plea under terms of state law that allows first-time offenders to enter a 
pre-trial program. 
</P>
<P>
The pre-trial program is designed to allow authorities to monitor Shackleford's 
activities and does not involve substance abuse treatment or counseling, Boylan 
said. 
</P>
<P>
If the player successfully completes terms of the six-month program, a 
disorderly person charge will be dropped and Shackleford's record cleared. 
</P>
<P>
Shackleford, 23, is the focus of news reports about an investigation of an 
alleged point-shaving scheme when he was at North Carolina State. 
</P>
</TEXT>
